WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.200
[Amit Varma]: This episode of The Seen and The Unseen is brought to you by Intel.

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:15.960
[Amit Varma]: In 1890, Lucy Jervis, the wife of Lord Harris, the Governor of Bombay, challenged her husband to a game of cricket.

00:00:16.240 --> 00:00:18.560
[Amit Varma]: It took place in the Hill Resort of Mahabaleshwar.

00:00:18.840 --> 00:00:24.240
[Amit Varma]: Jervis, or Lady Harris, led a team of 13 women, while her husband's team had the usual 11 men.

00:00:24.600 --> 00:00:27.960
[Amit Varma]: A magazine called Cricket carried this account from a correspondent.

00:00:27.960 --> 00:00:30.960
[Amit Varma]: Quote, We are all feeling quite exhausted with laughing.

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:34.040
[Amit Varma]: The ladies were most dreadfully in earnest, but so nervous.

00:00:34.280 --> 00:00:36.880
[Amit Varma]: Every run, every ball led to a comical situation.

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:42.280
[Amit Varma]: Their nervousness at running, the way they met in the middle of each wicket and consulted as to whether it was safe to go on,

00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:47.120
[Amit Varma]: and finally each would run back to her own wicket, the way they threw themselves on the ball in fielding

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:49.520
[Amit Varma]: and had to make a search in their petticoats for it.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:50.520
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:55.960
[Amit Varma]: Even at this distance, the condescension, the patronizing tone makes me so mad.

00:00:55.960 --> 00:00:57.960
[Amit Varma]: And that's not just a 19th century tone.

00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:02.440
[Amit Varma]: You hear it around you today, in private drawing rooms and public social media,

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:05.760
[Amit Varma]: where women's cricket is looked upon as a curiosity.

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:08.680
[Amit Varma]: In recent times, though, there have been stirrings of change.

00:01:08.880 --> 00:01:12.200
[Amit Varma]: The excerpt I read out is from a superb book called The Fire Burns Blue,

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:17.080
[Amit Varma]: A History of Women's Cricket in India by Karunia Keshav and the late Siddhant Pattnayak.

00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:21.320
[Amit Varma]: And my guest today is someone who's been part of the journey of women's cricket,

00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:26.840
[Amit Varma]: both as someone who played for India and as someone who has written with great insight and eloquence about the game.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:30.840
[Amit Varma]: And she's thrown herself headlong into another movement that I care a lot about,

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:33.400
[Amit Varma]: the one that's happening in the creator economy.

00:01:33.720 --> 00:01:36.920
[Amit Varma]: Can someone really be part of two revolutions in one lifetime?

